缘起
1999年，中途镇，咖啡馆，上午10点，中本聪准时出现在靠窗子的位置。

中本聪喜欢这个位置，不是因为他喜欢看风景，而是因为只有这个位置有电源插口。对，中本聪是个宅男程序员，他最近休假，每天都来咖啡馆写代码，因为他的人生理想之一就是每天可以在咖啡馆悠闲的编程。

那时，互联网的世界新生伊始，许多事物还没有名字，提到的时候尚需用手指指点点。

data.s9: The shadow of a black hole seen here is the closest we can come to an image of the black hole itself, a completely dark object from which light cannot escape. The black hole’s boundary — the event horizon from which the EHT takes its name — is around 2.5 times smaller than the shadow it casts and measures just under 40 billion km across. While this may sound large, this ring is only about 40 microarcseconds across — equivalent to measuring the length of a credit card on the surface of the Moon.

data.s7: It is a good notice. And indeed, users should not upload copyrighted content to the blockchain unless authorised to do so. It is the responsibility of the requester and the uploader to verify that the data isn't protected by copyright law or falls in the public domain. The same notice should apply to all directories of dir.sv, but ultimately the core issue remains on the content that is stored on the blockchain.

data.s5: Does indexing (dir.sv) violate copyright laws? No, but under certain conditions. In my opinion, the case would be similar to Google Images that indexes images, and just like their service the index can be removed upon request. As for the people who upload copyrighted content on the blockchain, their addresses are forever linked to it, so ultimately they could get in trouble - so anyone who uses the Internet and (un)knowingly repost copyrighted content.

A pseudoscience is a fake science that makes claims based on faulty or nonexistent scientific evidence. In most cases, these pseudosciences present claims in a way that makes them seem possible, but with little or no empirical support for these claims.

Graphology, numerology, and astrology, are all examples of pseudosciences. In many cases, these pseudosciences rely on anecdotes and testimonials to back up their often outlandish claims.
